<pretext>
    <article xml:id="notes">
        <worksheet margin="1in" bottom="1.25cm" xml:id="sec-VIII-1-sols">
        <title><m>\S VIII.1</m>: Antiderivatives and Indefinite Integrals</title>
            <page>
                <exercise workspace="2in">
                    <title>Motivation: Antiderivatives </title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            In many cases, we have information about the derivatives of a system, and would like to use 
                            this information to describe system behavior. The concept of "thinking backwards from derivative" can
                            be useful.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                
                </exercise>

                <exercise workspace="2in">
                    <title>Exercise: Antiderivative</title>
                    
                    
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Given <m>f(x) =x</m>, 
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Sketch <m>f'(x)</m>.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Sketch <m>F(x)</m> such that <m>F'(x) = f(x)</m>.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <m>f'(x) =1</m> is a constant function. However, a function <m>F(x)</m> satisfying <m>F'(x) = f(x)</m> 
                            is a quadratic function, and there are infinitely many of them.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>

                <exercise workspace="2in">
                    <title>Definition: Antiderivative</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            An <term>antiderivative</term> of <m>f(x) </m> is a function <m>F(x)</m> such that
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <m>F'(x) = f(x)</m>. We noticed above that if <m>F(x)</m> is an antiderivative of <m>f(x)</m>, then so is
                            <m>F(x) + C</m> for any constant <m>C</m>.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>

            </page>

            <page>
                <exercise workspace="2in">
                    <title>Notation: Indefinite Integrals</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            The family of antiderivative of <m>f(x)</m> with respect to <m>x</m> is notated 
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <m>\displaystyle \int f(x) \quad dx</m>, and is called the <term>indefinite integral of <m>f(x)</m>
                            with respect to <m>x</m></term>.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>

                <exercise>
                    <title>Practice: Verifying Indefinite Integrals</title>
                    
                    
                    <introduction>
                        <p>
                            Determine if the following are true or false.
                        </p>
                    </introduction>
                    <task workspace="1in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                <m>\displaystyle \int 2x \quad dx = x^2 +C</m>
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                True
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="1in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                <m>\displaystyle \int \sin(x) \quad dx = \cos(x) +C</m>
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                False
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="1in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                <m>\displaystyle \int x^3 \quad dx = x^4 +C</m>
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                False
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="1in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                <m>\displaystyle \int \frac{1}{x} \quad dx = \ln(x) +C</m>
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                True, though typically we'd like the antiderivative functions to be defined on the same domain 
                                as <m>f(x)</m>. To satisfy this, we'd notice <m>\displaystyle \int \frac{1}{x} \quad dx = \ln(|x|) +C</m>.
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="1in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                <m>\displaystyle \int 2x\cos(x^2) \quad dx = x^2\sin(x^2) +C</m>
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                False
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>
                </exercise>
            </page>

            <page>
                <exercise workspace="2in">
                    <title>Antiderivatives with Initial Condition</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            If we also know a specific value that an antiderivative must satisfy, then we can determine 
                            the equation of a unique antiderivative:
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            For example, if we know <m>F'(x) = x</m> and <m>F(0) =5</m>, this specifies a specific quadratic function
                            whose <m>y</m>-intercept is <m>(0,5)</m>.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>

                <exercise>
                    <title>Practice: Finding Antiderivatives</title>
                    <introduction>
                        <p>
                            Find the antiderivative <m>F(x)</m> of each function <m>f(x)</m> satisfying the given initial condition.
                        </p>
                    </introduction>
                    <task workspace="1.5in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                <m>f(x) = 2x</m>, <m>F(0) = -3</m>
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                <m>F(x) = x^2 - 3</m>
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>
                    <task workspace="1.5in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                <m>f(x) = 2x</m>, <m>F(-3) = 0</m>
                            </p>
                        </statement>

                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                <m>F(x) = x^2 - 9</m>
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="1.5in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                <m>f(x) = \sin(x)</m>, <m>F(0) = -2</m>
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                <m>F(x) = -\cos(x) -1</m>
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="1.5in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                <m>f(x) =\frac{1}{x}</m>, <m>F(e) = 5</m>
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                <m>F(x) = \ln(|x|)+ 4</m>
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>

        </worksheet>
